  "query": "How does the effectiveness of no-take marine protected areas on fish communities differ between the Mediterranean Sea and the Indian Ocean?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across studies of no\u2011take marine protected areas, 15 studies were in the Indian Ocean and 12 in the Mediterranean Sea [2682]. In both regions, site comparisons reported different fish community composition in no\u2011take areas versus fished areas after 3\u201316 years [2682]. For richness/diversity, studies including both regions often found higher species richness in no\u2011take areas, but one replicated Indian Ocean study found the effect on species richness/diversity after 15 years varied with sampling method [2682]. For abundance, multiple studies across regions (including the Mediterranean and Indian Oceans) reported higher fish abundance or biomass in no\u2011take areas, while other studies found similar or mixed effects depending on species, trophic position, size, habitat, or protection duration [2682]. Region\u2011specific findings included: Mediterranean\u2014more eggs of four commercially targeted fish species inside a no\u2011take reserve enforced for three years, and higher small\u2011scale commercial catch rates closest to a 22\u2011year no\u2011take reserve, decreasing with distance [2682]; Indian Ocean\u2014higher fish grazing rates in no\u2011take areas protected for 1 and 24 years, highest reef\u2011fish stock biomass in enforced no\u2011take areas compared to other management regimes, and most individuals of five fish species remaining within a no\u2011take reserve over nine years [2682].",
